BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:IU Eskenazi School of Art, Architecture + Design
DTSTART:20260423T213000Z
DTEND:20260423T233000Z
LOCATION:WYLIE HOUSE (307 E. SECOND STREET)
GEO:39.161697;-86.5309
SUMMARY:Making Indiana University: A Reading\, Conversation\, and Signing
  with Jim Capshew
DESCRIPTION:Blending institutional and environmental history\, Making Ind
 iana University: History\, Landscape\, and a Sense of Place (https://iuli
 brariespublishing.iu.edu/making-IU/) traces how the university's identity
  has been shapedŌĆömaterially and imaginativelyŌĆöby Dunn's Woods\, the e
 volving campus landscape\, and the narratives through which generations h
 ave understood this place.  In a setting central to IU's early history\, 
 author Jim Capshew (https://hpsc.indiana.edu/about/emeriti-faculty/capshe
 w-james.html) will introduce the book\, read from it\, and take questions
  from the audience. The event will be introduced by John Summerlot\, Dire
 ctor of Enterprise Risk &amp\; Incident Management at the IU Foundation. 
 It will conclude with a signing of a specially produced booklet featuring
  the Wylie House chapter\, along with commemorative image cards drawn fro
 m the volume. Following the program\, guests are invited to enjoy a self-
 guided tour of the Wylie House.  Light refreshments will be served.  The 
 event also celebrates IU Libraries Publishing (https://libraries.indiana.
 edu/libraries-publishing)\, the university's new open-access publisher of
  long-form scholarly\, creative\, and public-facing works. By making publ
 ications freely available worldwide at no cost to readers or authors\, IU
  Libraries Publishing advances Indiana University's public mission and en
 sures that its scholarship remains accessible to all.  This event will be
  of particular interest to IU alumni\, Bloomington residents\, faculty an
 d staff\, and anyone interested in university history\, environmental stu
 dies\, and the evolving story of Indiana University.  Doors will open at 
 5 p.m. This event is free and open to the public.  Free parking options a
 re available for visitors:Neighborhood Street Parking: Free street parkin
 g is available after 5 p.m.\, including in areas normally restricted to N
 eighborhood Zone permit holders.  Wylie House Museum Parking: Complimenta
 ry parking (no permit required) is available behind the Wylie House Museu
 m and adjacent to its Education Center (the gray barn). This lot includes
  one accessible parking space. Access these spaces via the alley behind t
 he museum\, from Grant Street and Lincoln Street.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  Blending institutional and environmenta
 l history\, <em><a href="https://iulibrariespublishing.iu.edu/making-IU/"
 >Making Indiana University: History\, Landscape\, and a Sense of Place</a
 ></em> traces how the university's identity has been shapedŌĆömaterially 
 and imaginativelyŌĆöby Dunn's Woods\, the evolving campus landscape\, and
  the narratives through which generations have understood this place.</p>
 <p>  In a setting central to IU's early history\, author <a href="https:/
 /hpsc.indiana.edu/about/emeriti-faculty/capshew-james.html" target="_blan
 k" rel="noopener">Jim Capshew</a> will introduce the book\, read from it\
 , and take questions from the audience. The event will be introduced by J
 ohn Summerlot\, Director of Enterprise Risk &amp\; Incident Management at
  the IU Foundation. It will conclude with a signing of a specially produc
 ed booklet featuring the Wylie House chapter\, along with commemorative i
 mage cards drawn from the volume. Following the program\, guests are invi
 ted to enjoy a self-guided tour of the Wylie House.</p><p>  Light refresh
 ments will be served.</p><p>  The event also celebrates <a href="https://
 libraries.indiana.edu/libraries-publishing">IU Libraries Publishing</a>\,
  the university's new open-access publisher of long-form scholarly\, crea
 tive\, and public-facing works. By making publications freely available w
 orldwide at no cost to readers or authors\, IU Libraries Publishing advan
 ces Indiana University's public mission and ensures that its scholarship 
 remains accessible to all.</p><p>  This event will be of particular inter
 est to IU alumni\, Bloomington residents\, faculty and staff\, and anyone
  interested in university history\, environmental studies\, and the evolv
 ing story of Indiana University.</p><p>  Doors will open at 5 p.m. This e
 vent is free and open to the public.</p><p>  Free parking options are ava
 ilable for visitors:</p><ul><li>Neighborhood Street Parking: Free street 
 parking is available after 5 p.m.\, including in areas normally restricte
 d to Neighborhood Zone permit holders.  </li><li>Wylie House Museum Parki
 ng: Complimentary parking (no permit required) is available behind the Wy
 lie House Museum and adjacent to its Education Center (the gray barn). Th
 is lot includes one accessible parking space. Access these spaces via the
  alley behind the museum\, from Grant Street and Lincoln Street.  </li></
 ul>
